player.seasonOutlook: The 10th-overall selection in the 2018 draft, Rosen started his rookie season on the bench, but was thrown to the wolves during a Week 3 loss to Chicago. Rosen went on to throw 11 touchdowns and 14 interceptions in 14 games. Granted his supporting cast was weak, but Rosen completed only 55 percent of his passes (second worst) and averaged 5.8 yards per attempt (third worst). He managed only two weekly fantasy finishes inside the top 20 and none were better than 14th. Rosen was infamously traded to Miami during the draft and is the likely Week 1 starter ahead of Ryan Fitzpatrick. Rosen figures to take a step forward in his second season, but he's learning a new offense on a rebuilding team. He's worth holding only in dynasty.

Keenum was traded to Washington after holding down the fort while playing all but one snap in Denver last season. The results weren't particularly impressive, as Keenum completed 62 percent of his passes (10th worst) and posted 6.6 yards per attempt (sixth worst). Despite ranking seventh in dropbacks, he was held to one top-12 fantasy week and finished 19th in total fantasy points at the position. The 31-year-old is a fringe NFL starter and will have his hands full holding off first-round pick Dwayne Haskins for Week 1 starting duties. Keenum isn't a good fantasy option.

The Giants shockingly selected Jones with the sixth overall pick in April's draft. The 6-foot-5, 221-pound Duke product was far from impressive in his final FBS season. Jones was off target on 9.4 percent of his throws (best in this class), but he was very conservative (8.1 aDOT), which led to a weak 6.8 YPA. Jones did deal with a ton of drops, but his weak efficiency and struggles throwing the deep ball are red flags. Jones is a good athlete who will add some value at the pro level with his legs. Eli Manning will be the team's starter as long as he's healthy and the Giants are competitive this season, but Jones figures to get a few starts late in the season. He's only a fantasy option in dynasty.

Davis is now 35 years old but continues to make an impact as a situational seam stretcher. Davis has ranked Top 10 in aDOT each of the past 10 seasons and has finished top 10 in both YPT and YPR each of the past three seasons. He's been limited to no more than 68 targets and hasn't cleared three touchdowns in a season since 2013, however, which also marks the season of his last top-15 fantasy campaign. Davis is Jordan Reed's handcuff but would only be a TE2 if Reed were to miss time.

Brate has finished top 15 among tight ends in pass routes each of the past three seasons but has seen his fantasy production progressively dip during that span. Brate posted a 57-660-8 line and was fantasy's No. 7 tight end in 2016. He fell to 10th in 2017 and 19th in 2018 despite appearing in all 32 of the team's games over that stretch. Brate's calling card has been touchdowns, as he's the only tight end who has scored at least six touchdowns each of the past three seasons. Brate was fantasy's No. 16 tight end during the six weeks O.J. Howard was out last season, which even puts a damper on his handcuff appeal. He has minimal fantasy value.

Swaim joins the Jaguars after pacing the Jason Witten-less Cowboys' tight end room in snaps (491) and targets (30), despite missing seven games last season. Despite playing a full-time role during the nine weeks he was active, Swaim was limited to a 26-242-1 line on 30 targets and sat 17th in fantasy points. The 2015 seventh-round pick entered the season with 11 career targets. He'll primarily be asked to block for Leonard Fournette in Jacksonville and has little fantasy value.

Seemingly eyeing an eventual successor to 29-year-old and contract-year Kyle Rudolph, Minnesota spent a second-round pick on Smith during April's draft. Smith is an undersized (6-foot-2, 242 pounds) receiving tight end and a work in progress as a blocker. Extremely young and raw, Smith turns 21 years old in August and was limited to 58 catches in 26 games at Alabama. Smith has terrific speed (4.63 40-yard dash), which helped him to 16.1 yards per reception, including 8.5 after the catch, last season. He'll need time to develop -- and is well positioned to do that behind Rudolph in 2019 -- but figures to emerge as a viable fantasy option in the next few years. Smith has minimal 2019 fantasy value barring a Rudolph injury.

Broncos GM John Elway likes tall, strong-armed pocket quarterbacks, so it was no surprise he selected Lock with the No. 42 pick in April's draft. Lock has an ideal frame (6-foot-4, 228 pounds), a very good arm, throws a good deep ball and offers some mobility (4.69 40-yard dash, 4.12 short shuttle). On the other hand, accuracy and struggles against pressure are concern areas. The Missouri product completed only 63 percent of his passes in 2018, which was actually the best of his career and required a massive drop in aDOT (8.5). Lock figures to make a few starts down the stretch this season, but he'll start out backing up Joe Flacco. His only fantasy value is in dynasty.

Clement was a popular 2018 fantasy sleeper but ended up resuming his role as a complementary player and saw his efficiency take a nosedive after a solid rookie season. Clement registered 444 yards and six touchdowns on 84 touches in 2017 before posting 451 yards and two scores on 90 touches in 2018 (10 games). Clement will battle with Wendell Smallwood and Boston Scott for change-of-pace and passing-down work behind Jordan Howard and Miles Sanders. He has little fantasy appeal.

The Jaguars selected Oliver in the third round of April's draft. Oliver was busy at San Jose State last season, playing 780 snaps and handling 103 targets, the latter of which was most in this rookie class.  Oliver struggled a bit with efficiency, including eight drops, and isn't particularly quick (4.47 short shuttle). Oliver has a decent-sized frame (6-foot-5, 249 pounds) and could develop into a two-way tight end in the pros. In the short term, expect him share tight ends duties with veterans Geoff Swaim and James O'Shaughnessy. He doesn't have much 2019 fantasy value.

Kroft signed with the Bills after spending his first four NFL seasons in Cincinnati. The 2013 third-round pick posted a 42-404-7 line in relief of Tyler Eifert in 2017 but fell behind C.J. Uzomah last season and then was lost for the season with a broken foot. Kroft could snag the occasional touchdown, but he'll spend a lot of time blocking and is a poor bet for consistent fantasy production in Buffalo's run-heavy offense. He's not worth a draft pick.

Clay signed with the Cardinals following a disappointing four-year tenure in Buffalo. Clay broke out way back in 2013, when he posted a 69-759-6 line and was fantasy's No. 8 tight end. Since that point, he's missed at least one game in five consecutive seasons, while averaging 70.8 targets, 47.2 receptions, 485.4 yards and 2.4 touchdowns per season. He failed to post a single top-15 fantasy season during the span. Clay is now 30 years old and will compete with Ricky Seals-Jones and Maxx Williams for top billing in the Arizona tight end room. There's not much upside here in a new-look and rebuilding offense.

Uzomah returns to Cincinnati after posting career-high marks in targets (64), receptions (43), receiving yards (439) and touchdowns (three) last season. Only seven tight ends played more snaps. Despite the step forward in 2018, Uzomah is expected to resume backup duties behind Tyler Eifert this season. Uzomah was out-targeted 15-to-7 by Eifert during the three games the two played together in full last season. Of course, Eifert has missed at least eight games four of the past five seasons, so Uzomah could sneak back into TE2 territory if Eifert goes down again. That's not enough to make him worth a draft pick.

James signed with Detroit after spending the first four seasons of his career in Pittsburgh. James played a ton of snaps during his time in Pittsburgh (2,379 to be exact) but was asked to block on 50 percent of those plays, which allowed him only 42.75 targets per season. Despite his massive 6-foot-7, 261-pound frame, James never scored more than three touchdowns in a season. His best fantasy season was a 22nd-place finish in 2017. Especially with first-round pick T.J. Hockenson in the fold, James' primary job will be blocking in a run-first Detroit offense, which means he has almost no fantasy appeal.

The Packers selected Sternberger in the third round of April's draft. The Texas A&M product is the presumed successor to 32-year-old Jimmy Graham, whose play slipped in 2018. Sternberger is fresh off a highly productive season, in which he paced all incoming tight ends with 10 touchdowns and caught 48 of 51 catchable targets. Sternberger is an athletic 6-foot-4, 251 pounds, a good route-runner with sure hands and he sports good post-catch and big-play ability. His frame raises questions about his potential blocking contributions in the pros, but he has plenty of experience in the area. Sternberger won't be a fantasy asset in 2019 as long as Graham is healthy, but could emerge as Green Bay's starter as soon as 2020.
